Dimensionality Reduction and Manifold Learning¶

In this section I discuss some of the motivations and techniques of dimensionality reduction, before diving into sklearn implementations. Note that these all can be categorized as unsupervised learning, as the labels are not needed.

Two of the most important reasons in machine learning to reduce dimension are to increase the density of the data, and to remove noise features. A third reason is for visualization.

For a learning technique to have any statistical power (reasonably low variance), it's required that the instances be somewhat dense, by which is meant a relatively low average distance between neighboring instances. The problem in higher-dimensional space is that in order to achieve a similar density as in a lower-dimensional space, exponentially more instances are needed. It can be shown for instance that as dimension $d$ increases, the percent of interior mass in a small sliver near the boundary of the $d$-dimensional sphere appraoches 100. Intuitively, points drawn uniformly from the $d$-dimensional sphere will relatively likely have at least one or more components that are large in magnitude i.e. near the boundary, while it's relatively unlikely that all entries will be small in magnitude i.e. near the center of the sphere. The random variable defined by uniformly choosing a point (from a fixed sample-size dataset) in the $d$-sphere and taking the distance $\sqrt{(x_1-y_1)^2 + ... + (x_d - y_d)^2}$ between it and its nearest neighbor has an expected value that increases without bound with $d$. This can be easily seen, in the case of any distribution in fact, simply by noting that the terms $(x_i-y_i)^2$ do not go to zero and hence give rise to a divergent series. On the other hand if we allow the sample-size to grow (exponentially) with $d$, then the average nearest neighbor distance is stable.

That was to say, there's a lot of space in high-dimensional space. Reducing the dimension, in a clever way, increases the density of the dataset, and can give more statistical power and result in a model with better genralization. As an added bonus, decreasing the number of features also reduces training time and needed memory.

On the other hand, removing features which represent only noise, or are relatively constant accross all instances, or which are redundant because their information is already given by (functions of) other features, can only help training and model generalization.

For many types of problems the "manifold hypothesis" will be reasonable. That is, though the data lives in $N$-dimensional feature space, there are not fully $N$ degrees of freedom, i.e. the data really lives near an $n$-dimensional manifold embedded in $N$-space where $n < N$. Consider a dataset of facial images, each pixel in the range [0,255]. Since all faces look more or less alike, the pixels are highly constrained in the values they can take on, based on their index and the value of pixels in the image. The intrinsic (and latent) dimensionality of the dataset is much lower than num_pixels $\times$ num_pixels.

There are broadly three categories of dimensionality reduction techniques: matrix-factorization, generative models, and manifold learning.

Principle Component Analysis (PCA)¶

This a projection technique that finds the directions of greatest variance in the dataset, under the constraint that these directions be pairwise orthogonal, and then (if fit or fit_transform is called) projects the instances into the space spanned by these directions. The directions are called the principle components. These are the rows of $V^T$ from the SVD $D = U \Sigma V^T$ of the (tensorial 2-dimensional) dataset $D$. The number of directions to project down into is a hyperparameter that can be tuned with grid search. It's usually a good idea to start by choosing enough directions such that a high proportion, say 0.95, of the variance is captured. Another technique is to plot explained variance (on the y-axis) and n-directions (on the x-axis), and use the "elbow method" heuristic to choose a reasonable baseline number of directions. Another hyperparameter to play with is whiten, which when set to True scales the components to unit variance (useful for some downstream training algorithms).

Sklearn implements decomposition.PCA with a parameter svd_solver='auto'$\in$ ('auto', 'full', 'arpack', 'randomized'). It will use 'full' or 'randomized' depending on the size of the dataset ('arpack' is good for sparse features), the former being $O(m \times n^2) + O(n^3)$ and the later being $O(m \times d^2) + O(d^3)$. Sklearn also implements IncrementalPCA for partial fitting and for use with np.memmap, for mini-batch out-of-core learning, and KernelPCA which is used for nonlinear projection and can preserve clusters and twists in the dataset better than standard PCA. It's standard to use grid search to try these out, with different hyperparameters, kernel functions, etc..

Note that SVD finds further application in sparse-matrix document representation problems that arise in NLP, such as latent semantic analysis and factor analysis.

Note that the orthogonal directions of greatest variance are discovered automatically by PCA without the input of a priori assumptions. This makes PCA useful for exploratory data analysis where a user wishes to discover unknown and useful representations of the instances.

Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA)¶

This techniques makes the fundamental assumption that the instances in the dataset are given by a generative, layered probability model. Formallly, the assumption is that the instance (in $m$-dimensional feature space) $d_i$ belongs to $k$ distinct topics ($k$ a hyperparameter) with $k$-dimensional strength vector $\theta_i \sim Dir(\alpha, k)$, such that $\theta_{i,s} \in [0,1]$ and $\sum_{s=1}^k \theta_{i,s} = 1$, and that each feature $j$ of instance $d_i$ belongs to topic $t_{i,j} \sim Categorical(\theta_i)$ and has value $v_{i,j} \sim Categorical(\beta_{t_{i,j}})$.

This is an old technique of topic modeling that finds most common application in the field of NLP in the context where we wish to prescribe topics to documents based on the unigrams in the document, i.e. by treating the document as a bag-of-words. To describe the assumption more intuitively, a document $d$ belongs to certain topics with different strengths, say sports=0.2, politics=0.75, biology=0.05. To choose the $j^{th}$ word, $j = 1, 2, ..., m$, (note the words are unordered due to the unigram assumption), we first choose a topic $t$ randomly, where we model the choice as a 3-sided die roll with probabilities 0.2, 0.75, 0.05. With this choice of topic in hand, we choose a value $w$ randomly, where we model this choice as a $z$-sided die roll with probabilities $p_1, ..., p_z$, where $z$ and the $p_i$'s are dependent on our choice of $t$. For instance if $t=$ sports we have say "net" with $p=0.03$, "ball" with $p=0.09$, "player" with $p=0.12$, "horse" with $p=0.001$, "measure-theory" with $p=0$, etc..

The choice of categorical variables is intuitive and obvious, albeit simplifying. The choice of the Dirichlet variable is chosen however out of analytical convenience: the Dirichlet with parameter $k$ outputs a $k$-dimensional vector with entries $v \in [0,1]$ summing to 1, a natural choice if we want to take this vector and use it as the parameter of a categorical variable. (The Dirichlet has another parameter called the "concentration" which governs the distribution of mass in the output vector (e.g. the mass could be uniform accross all entries, or perhaps favor certain entries, etc.)). But the best part is that the Dirichlet distribution is also the conjugate prior of the categorical. If a variable is categorical whose parameter has a Dirichlet prior distribution, then conditioning on data to yield a posterior distribution for the parameter yields another Dirichlet. If the prior Dirichlet has concentration parameter $\alpha = (\alpha_1, ..., \alpha_k)$ and the data is $c = (c_1, ..., c_k)$ where $c_i$ is the number of occurances of category $i$, then the posterior is Dirichlet with concentration $\alpha' = (\alpha_1 + c_1, ..., \alpha_k + c_k)$.

In practice, the goal is to learn the greeks (to find those which make the dataset (relatively) highly likely), given some initial assumptions about prior distributions (usually assume uniformly weighted Dirichlet and categorical priors), and hyperparameter $k$ governing the number of topics, as well as the topics themselves. Note that this is an unsupervised technique and the topics are learned automatically. There are various ways of implementing this, including a full Bayesian analysis, MCMC, variational techniques, etc., but that's beyond the scope of this tutorial. The objective is to reduce the dimension of the dataset down to the number of topics, and transform the instances to their strength vectors.

One learning algorithm (mean-field variational inference):¶

Once the learning is complete and we want to transform our dataset, we map the instances to their strength vectors without relearning the topics, by finding the strength vector which maximizes the instance's likelihood.

If we already have labels giving the topics to which documents belong, LDA is not a good idea because it's much weaker and has more variance than certain supervised techniques. But LDA is a good choice when we do not have labels and we wish to perform some such analysis as clustering, or to gain insights about our data via the cycle of machine learning $\rightarrow$ human learning $\rightarrow$ machine learning. Note that LDA has a lot of variance, and will not perform well if:

  1. the training instances do not contain words (feature values) which can be used effectively to discriminate their cluster

  2. the training instances belong to mutiple topics

  3. the training instances are too short or have a low signal-to-noise ratio.

Sklearn implements LatentDirichletAllocation, with useful hyperparameters and online learning capabilities. Note that after calling fit, an object has a components_ member when can be utilized to examine the topics. This is useful for learning about documents (or sets of products) because we can actually see which items categorize the different topics.

There is a large familiy of manifold learning techniques, including MDS, Isomap, SpectralEmbedding, LocallyLinearEmbedding, TSNE, and others, but only LLE and tSNE are at discussed here. The following practical tips apply to all techniques

  1. Make sure all features are the same scale (consider using StandardScaler)
  2. Noisy data can "short-circuit" the manifold, creating bridges between clusters
  3. For some algorithms duplicate points in the dataset can cause difficulty

Note that none of the manifold learning techniques in this family are particularly scalable, save the Barnes-Hut implementation of tSNE, which however is only used for visualization (2-3-d embedding) and not for general dimensionality reduction.

Locally Linear Embedding (LLE)¶

This is a nonlinear manifold learning technique whose spirit is similar to that of multi-dimensional scaling (MDS) encountered in the section on random forests. The algorithm is easily understood as an optimization problem. Given a dataset $X$ and hyperparameters n_components and n_neighbors, it proceeds for each instance $x_i$ to find the n_neighbors nearest neighbors $x_{i,j}$, and then compute and store the weights $w_{i,j} \in R$ which minimize $||x_i - \sum_{j=1}^{\textrm{n_neighbors}} w_{i,j}x_{i,j}||_2^2$ subject to $\sum_j w_{i,j} = 1$. It then fixes the weights and for each instance $x_i$ computes the n_components-dimensional vector $z_i$ which minimizes $||z_i - \sum_{j=1}^{\textrm{n_neighbors}} w_{i,j}z_{i,j}||_2^2$.

The sklearn implementation complexity, with $n$ feature dimension, $m$ num samples, $k$ nearest neighbors, projecting to $d$ dimensions, is:

$O(mnlog(m)log(k)) + O(mnk^3) + O(dm^2)$. The $m^2$ in the last term presents this technique from scaling to large datasets.

t-distributed Stochastic Nearest-Neighbors Embedding (tSNE)¶

Most commonly used as a nonlinear visualization technique (by reducing dimension to 2 or 3), the very popular tSNE proceeds by computing dataset probabilities $p_{i,j}$ for each pair of points ($p_{i,i} := 0$), modeling the probability that $x_j$ is the nearest neighbor to $x_i$ under a probability distribution centered at $x_i$. Note that effectively the hyperparamter perplexity controls how many pairwise probabilities are computed for each point, what basically determines how many points tSNE believes live in each cluster. The points are then mapped to lower-dimensional space, where the corresponding (but perhaps differently defined i.e. with a different distribution) probabilities $q_{i,j}$ are computed. These sets of probabilities are individually combined into probabilities over the dataset and embedding, $P$ and $Q$, respectively. Then a difference measure $D(P,Q)$, a modified Kullback-Liebler divergence serving as a cost function, is calculated. The mappings are chosen to minimize $D(P,Q)$. This later goal can be accomplished basically with gradient descent.

It's strongly noted that tSNE performs better than other manifold learning techniques at datasets whose points live in distinct manifolds, e.g. the MNIST handwritten digits dataset. This is roughly because the cost function of tSNE relatively strongly penalizes the mapping of close points in the dataset to far-away points in the embedding. Therefore, tSNE is "good at" preserving clusters.

There are many algorithm subtleties that I glossed over, which for instance make the implementation stochastic, reduce its sensitivity to outliers, provide for hyperparameter tuning, etc., etc.. Go to the sklearn documentation and follow the links therein to learn more.

One of the most important things going for tSNE is that no assumptions are made about how many clusters are in the dataset. This is an advantage over one of the main drawbacks of techniques where the number of clusters has to be assumed - if $k$ clusters are sought, then $k$ clusters the algorithm will find, regardless of how many clusters actually exist in the dataset

Here, I will discuss only the salient considerations of practical use. tSNE plots require careful consideration and it's easy to mislead oneself.

General weaknesses of any tSNE implementation:

  1. It's not clear how well tSNE works for dimensionality reduction for $d > 3$, $d$ the embedding dimension. tSNE is primarily used for visualization. The local structure of the data might not be preserved well if $d > 3$ due to the heavy tails of the t-distribution.

  2. tSNE is likely to run into problems when the intrinsic dimension of the dataset is large, even about 100 or larger, as is the case with a dataset so straightforward as the Olivetti faces dataset. This is because the assumption that the manifold on which the data lives is locally Euclidean is likely violated. A technique to get around this issue would be to first reduce the dimensionality in another way, say PCA, or with an autoencoder (an unsupervised (and nonlinear) NN technique for dimensionality reduction by learning useful representations of datasets).

  3. The cost function of tSNE is not convex, and hence there's an array of hyperparamters to play with that control convergence, and different runs (especially with different hyperparameter values) may lead to different plots by virtue of the training phase terminating in a local optimum of the cost function.

Sklearn's TSNE has a parameter method='barnes_hut' $\in$ ('exact', 'barnes_hut). The former is $O(dN^2)$ while the later is $O(dNlog(N))$ ($d$ == n_components == embedding dimension), meaning the former is infeasible for hundred-thousand+ sample-size $N$ datasets while the later takes hours (whereas PCA takes minutes). The Barnes-Hut implementation is limited however to embeddings in 2- and 3-dimensional space. Either algorithm is stochastic, hence different runs can result in different plots.

Other considerations when using method='barnes_hut':

  1. Only works for dense data input
  2. Utilize the angle=0.5 parameter which governs the tradeoff between speed and accuracy (w.r.t. the 'exact' method). Values in the range [0.2, 0.8] lead to similar results, while going below 0.2 quickly increases computational time and going above 0.8 quickly increases error.

Hyperparameter tuning and plot interpretation:

  1. perplexity=30

This is the tradeoff between favoring local and global shape by virtue of effectively assuming the number of instances per cluster. Typical values may be in the range 5-50, but perplexity must always be tuned according to the total number of instances: namely when total number of instances increases, perplexity must be increased to compensate. With lower values, probably meaningless local structure tends to dominate the plot; with higher values it becomes likely the plot will always look like one big blog (espectially if perplexity > $N$). Different values (even within the reasonable scope) tend to lead to very different plots. For this reason it's almost always important to examine multiple plots with different perplexity values.

  1. learning_rate=200.0, n_iter=1000, n_iter_without_progress=200

As far as iterations, the most important thing is just to make sure the plot (the embeddings) becomes stable. What usually happens is that clusters and intermediate shapes in the embedding will form and disintegrate repeatedly, until a stable configuration is assumed permanently. Generally learning_rate $\in [10.0, 300.0]$, n_iter $\in [1000, 10000]$, n_iter_without_progress $\in [250, 1000]$ are acceptable, but other values may be tried out as well, and certainly if the dataset is somewhat large or atypical.

  1. early_exaggeration=12.0

Controls how tigtly clusters in the dataset are mapped together in the embedding, and how far apart different clusters end up. This hyperparamter is not very critical in terms of the outputted plot.

  1. metric='euclidean'

This is what's used to compute distances between instances. If the distances are precomputed (i.e. the $X$ passed to fit or fit_transform is a distance or dissimilarity matrix) then pass 'precomputed'.

  1. Things to keep in mind about plots

    • Sizes of the clusters (in terms of bounding box) in the embedding mean nothing in relation to the cluster sizes in the dataset

    • Distance between clusters in the embedding mean nothing in relation to the distances between clusters in the dataset

    • Shapes, knots, and other topological features might not be preserved in the embedding.

Unsupervised learning¶

Introduction¶

The previous sections (sans the one on dimensionality reduction) mostly dealt with problems in the category of supervised learning. Supervised learning has become extremely powerful at narrowly defined tasks, where the data being processed is relatively unchanging through time, and when at training time we have plenty of labeled instances. It can uncover some hidden patterns in the dataset, but the primary task is characterized by the objective of sending (previously unseen) instances to labels, examples of which we have seen in the past. Indeed, supervised learning is far and away the best method for such tasks. Unsupervised learning, while it can be stated as "machine learning without labels", is best understood, just as in the case of supervised learning, by what it seeks to accomplish, what it can do, rather than by what it lacks. Indeed, unsupervised learning deals with unlabeled data, and so it can not hope to send instances to labels, so what is the purpose?

Unsupervised learning discovers the structure in data by learning representations of the instances other than their original form, vectors (or tensors) of the form (feature1_value, feature2_value, ..., featurem_value). In other words it's capable of finding hidden features and patterns in the dataset. The following topics will be discussed in more depth later, but for now here are a few examples. In clustering, the algorithm seeks to identify high density regions (in feature space) in the dataset, and then map the instances to the index of the cluster to which they belong, or to a vector of affinities to the different clusters. These are but 1-d and num_clusters-d representations of the data, respectively. In dimensionality reduction, the algorithm maps instances to vectors (or perhaps tensors) which better represent them (e.g. as a linear combination of principle components in PCA, or as a topic-strength vector in LDA). In density estimation, the algorithm seeks to represent instances by their affinities to learned probability densities (or in general high density regions). In anomaly detection, we go one step further - if all affinities are low, the instance could be categorized as an outlier or anomaly. At large scale if many new instances are being categorized as such, we have data drift - instances are now coming from a different distribution than the one on which we learned. Supervised learning algorithms are not capable of the things just mentioned.

What is the point of finding these representations? Usually either to learn about the dataset in an active way (where we seek to achieve human understanding and/or perhaps establish a feedback loop between human input and machine learning output), or to enable/improve another machine learning task further down the pipeline. Indeed, it's very common that supervised and unsupervised tasks are combined, complementing each other in fact, in a pipeline applied to an overarching application goal - so common that it has a name: semisupervised learning. We have already seen how dimensionality reduction as in tSNE can be of assistance in the active learning. Clustering can also help here, by identifying (an interval of) how many distinct high density regions (probably) exist in the dataset. Clustering can also be used in various creative ways to propagate labels to all or many instances in a dataset, in a sitatuation where only some instances have labels (or none, in which case human input is required), to form a training set for a supervised model further down the pipeline. Dimensionality reduction can be used to speed up training and even improve generalization of models further down the pipeline. Similarly, feature engineering and regularization, two things which are applications of the representation learning which categorizes unsupervised learning, can improve generalization of models further down the pipeline. Anomaly detection can identify outliers which perhaps should be excluded from the training sets of models further down the pipeline, and can identify when the data begins to drift (and perhaps then trigger a new training phase of some model further down the pipeline). Occasionally, an unsupervised task might even be the primary application objective. This is the case with recommender systems, for instance by matrix-factorization (dimensionality reduction) of a user-rating matrix. This is also the case with anomaly retection, for instance when a credit card company tries to detect fraudulent transactions based on abnormal behavior.

4 categories into which most unsupervised tasks fall (and a few typical applications):

  1. Clustering (market segmentation; label propagation)

  2. Density Estimation / Anomaly Detection (remove bad training instances / trigger retraining for downstream model; fraud detection)

  3. Dimensionality Reduction (noise-reduction / eliminate redundant/excessive features to improve downstream model; visualization (active learning))

  4. Representation Learning (unsupervised pretraining - neural network techniques to find useful features)

Note that the lines between these categories are not always clear. For instance, clustering and representation learning can be considered forms of dimensionality reduction; density estimation, for instance Gaussian Mixture Models, can be considerd a form of clustering.

Finally, unsupervised methods apply to time-series analysis, e.g. hidden markov models. Unsupervised methods find application in reinforcement learning as well, when the reward is unknown and evolving.

An example of a real world machine learning application involving semisupervised- and active learning:

Setting: An insurance company has plenty of claims, say human-written police reports of auto accidents, as well as driver and circumstantial meta-data, perhaps from years back, digitally and on paper.

ML job 1: A neural-network model is built for the perceptual problem of gleaning the information off the paper claims, logging it in a (NoSQL) data store. (Note this step itself will probably involve semisupervised- and active learning)

ML job 2: Representation learning (unsupervised) takes place on the output from the previous step, to map to unstructured textual data into useful numerical vector format.

ML job 3: Density estimation (unsupervised) takes place, finding plenty of outlier instances from the output of the previous step.

ML job 4: Clustering takes place on the outliers, and there are identified $k$ well-defined (in terms of density) clusters of outliers.

ML job 5: Active learning takes place: samples from each cluster are examined by a human expert and given labels, for instance "drunk driver", "accidental elopement by small child", "runaway self-driving car", etc.. Clustering can then be used again to propagate labels accross outlier clusters.

ML job 6: A neural-network (supervised) model is built to classify human-written police reports to the appropriate bucket of claim type, e.g. "valid claim" for some, and "no way we're covering this" for others, for instance a drunk driving accident.

ML job 7: An ongoing density estimation (unsupervised) task is run on (mini?)batches of new incoming data, to detect when some really weird claim comes along which goes straight to human evaluation, bypassing the supervised model prediction, or to detect when by-and-large the format of the human-written police reports suddenly changes, triggering a retraining from step 1 onwards.

Clustering¶

The objective is to discover high density regions (in feature space) in the dataset. There are many algorithms to accomplish this. When selecting an algorithm, use the below chart to narrow down the choices based on the following important considerations:

  1. Does the algorithm need to be scalable?
  2. Does the number of clusters need to be assumed (this is typically a complication) or is it learned?
  3. Would different sizes/shapes of the clusters, and their global configuration, come into play?

Here are only covered the best of the above, in terms of their speed, scalability, and utility, namely cluster.KMeans, cluster.AggomerativeClustering, and cluster.DBSCAN (and cluster.OPTICS which is a DBSCAN extension). If these don't help your problem, or the problem suggests other methods, then refer to the chart above.

K-means clustering¶

The algorithm learns n_clusters centroids by first initializing them randomly (but by default rather smartly, by making them far apart (controlled by the init='k-means++' hyperparameter)), and then proceeds by assigning instances to a cluster according to their closest centroid; recompute the centroids by averaging over the cluster; reassign the instances; recompute the centroids; and so forth (it does this is a smart way by exploiting the triangle inequality due to an innovation (controlled by the algorithm hyperparameter)) until convergence criteria are met. Note the algorithm is stochastic hence different runs can result in different cluster assignments by virtue of settling in a local optimum. It's possible to implement out-of-core learning by virtue of the MiniBatchKMeans class, which has the same API. It's noted that mini-batch-k-means is cheaper and produces a similar result (albeit quality slighty reduced) to the full-batch algorithm.

Note that k-means is sensitive to cluster geometry - it's essential to scale the features. This will not guarantee nice, spherical clusters, but it might help. It's also usually a good idea to try dimensionality reduction before k-means (or most any clustering algorithm)

The sklearn default implementation is average $O(NT)$ (but worst-case exponential!) where $N$ is the number of instances and $T$ is the number of starts. Since k-means is stochastic, the full algorithm is performed n_init=10 times and only the centroids from the best run are kept, where the best run is that which minimizes the dataset inertia, the mean within-cluster sum-of-squares distances. (Note dataset inertia decreases as n_clusters increases, hence inertia alone is not a reliable way to guage clustering algorithm performance.) Because inertia is not normalized is suffers from the curse of dimensionality, hence it's a good idea to try dimensionality reduction before k-means if the original feature space dimension is high.

In general the only hyperparameters to tune are n_clusters=8, tolerance=0.0001 (the stopping criterion: frobenious-norm change in centroids from one iteration to the next), and n_init=10, and max_iter=300.

See below for example applications of k-means to semi-supervised learning.

# Here is an example of using clustering to label an unlabeled dataset.
# We choose representatives from each cluster and label them manually, and then
# propagate the labels to all instances. We conclude by checking the accuracy against the true labels.
# Note it's in general not a good idea to manually classify centroids: they are only cluster averages and
# hence it can be difficult for a human to discern what the correct label would be (a 9 might look like a 4, etc.)
# because the features (in this case the images) will be blurred from averaging

from IPython.display import clear_output

km = KMeans(n_clusters=40)

def get_representatives_idx(X, clusterer):
    preds = list(clusterer.predict(X))
    representatives_idx = [preds.index(rep) for rep in np.unique(preds)]
    return representatives_idx

# Fit and manually classify representatives from each cluster.
km.fit(X_pca)
representatives_idx = get_representatives_idx(X_pca, km)
representatives = X[representatives_idx]
labels = []
for representative in representatives:
    plt.imshow(representative.reshape(28,28), cmap='gray')
    plt.show()
    label = int(input('label: '))
    labels.append(label)
    clear_output(wait=True)

# Now that we have the labeled representatives, we propagate the labels to their cluster-mates
y_manual = np.zeros(X.shape[0])
preds = km.predict(X_pca)
representatives_cluster_idx = km.predict(X_pca[representatives_idx])
for i, idx in enumerate(representatives_cluster_idx):
    y_manual[preds == idx] = labels[i]
    
y_manual = y_manual.astype('int')
y = y.astype('int')
acc = float(np.sum(y == y_manual) / y.shape)
print(f"Label propagation accuracy: {acc}")



    















    






Label propagation accuracy: 0.7361





















We see the accuracy we get from the above technique is only ~70%. Could be much better - we can't hope to make a proper supervised model down the pipeline if ~30% of our dataset is mislabeled.


We can make the following improvements. Instead of picking just any representative for each cluster, we can pick the instance closest to the center. This should reduce the probability that the representative actually belongs to another cluster than the one to which its label will be propagated. Next, we don't label all instances, but only those that are within the percentage closeness percentile to the centroid. (Downstream we can then train a model on only these (thusly labeled) instances (effectively identifying the rest as outliers and excluding them from training)).

def get_representatives_idx(X, clusterer, closest=True):
    '''Takes a fitted KMeans object; returns index array of instances that are
    representative of their own cluster'''
    if not closest:
        def _get_representatives_idx(X, clusterer):
            preds = list(clusterer.predict(X))
            representatives_idx = [preds.index(rep) for rep in np.unique(preds)]
            return representatives_idx
        return _get_representatives_idx(X, clusterer)
    
    X_dist = clusterer.transform(X)
    representatives_idx = np.argmin(X_dist, axis=0)
    return representatives_idx


def get_closest_percentile_idx(percentile, X, clusterer):
    '''Takes a fitted KMeans object; returns boolean index array of instances within 
    `percentile` distance from their cluster centroid'''
    X_dist_from_centroids = clusterer.transform(X)
    X_dist_from_own_centroid = X_dist_from_centroids[np.arange(len(X)), clusterer.labels_]
    n_clusters = clusterer.cluster_centers_.shape[0]
    for i in range(n_clusters):
        cluster_idx = (clusterer.labels_ == i)
        cluster_dist = X_dist_from_own_centroid[cluster_idx]
        cutoff_distance = np.percentile(cluster_dist, percentile)
        above_cutoff_idx = (X_dist_from_own_centroid > cutoff_distance)
        X_dist_from_own_centroid[cluster_idx & above_cutoff_idx] = -1
    
    return (X_dist_from_own_centroid != -1)


km = KMeans(n_clusters=40)


# Fit and manually classify representatives from each cluster.
km.fit(X_pca)

percentile = 50
closest_idx = get_closest_percentile_idx(percentile, X_pca, km)
X_closest = X[closest_idx]
X_pca_closest = X_pca[closest_idx]
y_closest = y[closest_idx]

representatives_idx = get_representatives_idx(X_pca_closest, km)
representatives = X_closest[representatives_idx]
labels = []
for representative in representatives:
    plt.imshow(representative.reshape(28,28), cmap='gray')
    plt.show()
    label = int(input('label: '))
    labels.append(label)
    clear_output(wait=True)
    

# Now that we have the labeled representatives, we propagate the labels to their cluster-mates
y_manual_closest = np.zeros(y_closest.shape)
preds = km.labels_[closest_idx]
representatives_cluster = km.predict(X_pca_closest[representatives_idx])
for i, cluster in enumerate(representatives_cluster):
    y_manual_closest[preds == cluster] = labels[i]
    
y_manual_closest = y_manual_closest.astype('int')
y_closest = y_closest.astype('int')
acc = float(np.sum(y_closest == y_manual_closest) / y_closest.shape)
print(f"Label propagation accuracy: {acc}")

This is about as good as we are going to get from this technique without brutally increasing the amount of human work (labeling). Not a bad labelling accuracy at ~90%, for only having manually labeled 60 instances (meanwhile the labels were propagated to about 6000 instances (the 20% percentile in closeness to cluster centroids)). But we can get better results by using different techniques. We can take our 60 (for sure correctly) labeled representatives, and attempt to build another type of supervised model, and then use the supervised model to predict the weights of all other instances (or those within a percentile of the of the 60 representatives). We can go a step further after that are try uncertainly sampling. We manually label any instances about which our supervised model is somewhat uncertain (i.e. equal-ish probability (or score) of belonging to any class according to the model), and retrain a new supervised model on the original representatives and the thus labeled uncertain instances. We can iterate this process until the performance improvement is not worth the human effort. Of course in realistic cases we don't have the true labels, so we have to be clever about terminating the process. Or, we can try another clustering technique, for instance DBSCAN, and implement an analogous scheme to propagate labels.















DBSCAN¶














This is a simple but effective algorithm that can identify an arbitrary amount of clusters of any shape, assuming that the clusters are defined by relatively high point density and that they're separated by areas of sufficiently low point density.




Algorithm:


Given hyperparamters eps=0.5 and min_samples=5


Compute the epsilon neighborhood of radius eps around each point (w.r.t. some metric, usually euclidean).


If a point has at least min_samples other points in its epsilon neighborhood, then it's a core sample; if a point is not a core sample and also isn't in the neighborhood of one, then it's an outlier; a point can be neither core nor outlier, being itself not core but in the neighborhood of a core sample.


Clusters are formed by unioning the epsilon neighborhoods of pairs of core samples which are in each others neighborhoods.


The large points represent core samples; the smaller points non-core samples; the black points outliers



Note that the algorithm is deterministic in finding the core samples and clusters (although different runs may produce a permutation of the cluster indices) and outliers, but different runs can assign non-core samples to different clusters if the orders of the dataset is different. This is because non-core samples are assigned to clusters via a first-pass algorithm.


Clearly, DBSCAN will have difficulty if the various clusters exhibit different densities. Consider two 2-d gaussian clusters in the plane, well separated by plenty of void space. If one cluster is very dense and the other very sparse, DBSCAN might label all instances in the sparse cluster as outliers, even though together they make up a legitimate cluster. For that reason it may be reasonable to normalize the data before DBSCAN, say with StandardScaler.


While the min_samples parameter controls in general how sensitive the algorithm is to noise, the eps parameter is crucially chosen according to the dataset, min_samples, as well as metric. Choosing an appropriate eps takes a good deal of analysis. (See below)


Note that due to the implementation there is no predict method to be called on fresh instances; there is only fit and fit_predict. This is because it's ambigous how to predict the cluster of a new instance (unlike k-means where it's simply the closest centroid): whether or not the instance is core it could belong to >1 cluster depending on which epsilon neighborhoods it falls in. This can be worked-aroung by training a supervised classification model on the core samples (or all samples sans the outliers) and their labels (cluster indices), and then using this model to predict the cluster of a new instance. (See below)


While computational complexity is somewhat scalable (approximately $O(mlog(m))$), The implementation is not memory efficient because it constructs a matrix of $N^2$ floats. Ways to get around this:


    

  1. Use OPTICS (in conjunction with the extract_dbscan method) or Birch. (See below)
    2. 

  2. A sparse radius neighborhood graph can be computed in a memory efficient way (missing entries will be assumed out of eps), and DBSCAN can be run over this by passing metric='precomputed'. (See below)
    3. 



After calling fit a DBSCAN object has the following 3 members:


    

  1. core_sample_indices_ (n_core_samples,) the index of the core samples (w.r.t. the training set)
    2. 

  2. components_ (n_core_samples, n_features) a copy of the core samples
    3. 

  3. labels_ (ninstances,) the cluster labels (w.r.t. the training set) (outliers get -1)
    4. 
















Selecting eps and min_samples¶
There are heuristics for choosing good parameters, but they are based on the original DBSCAN paper and a more recent, well-cited paper by Schubert et al in 2017. Basically these parameters are ideally set from domain expertise. For instance in a study of a database of proteins encoded by the percentages of the amino-acids of which they consist, expert knowledge may suggest that proteins with less than 10% total difference in their amino-acid distributions play similar biological roles and thus should constitute a cluster. From this information, an appropriate eps could be worked out from how a "10% difference" translates to the chosen norm.


Often times domain knowledge isn't available. Papers suggest setting min_samples to 2 * num_features or more for larger or noisier datasets. Setting eps is harder but there's a standard heuristic which involes user input: Look for an elbow in the k-neighbors-dist plot. This is a plot of instances' distances to their $k^{th}$ nearest neighbor, in descending order. Instances are on the x-axis (instance with farthest distance to $k^{th}$ neighbor on far right of support; instance with closest distance to $k^{th}$ neighbor on far left of support), and distances on the y-axis. The question stands, how to choose $k$? Luckily empirical evidence shows that it doesn't matter too much - most choices of $k$ will produce similar looking plots (slightly vertically translated, which will slightly affect the resulting choice of eps)- but it's probably reasonable to choose $k$ equal to min_samples.


Another heuristic is to look at a cluster-birth-death plot. This is where n-clusters is on the y-axis; eps on the x-axis, and we observe how many clusters form/merge as eps is increased. It's typical to see a plot with initially few clusters, and then one or several humps as eps increases, before n-clusters finally settles at 1 when eps is sufficiently large that all instances form a single cluster.


Another heuristic is to look at a cluster-support plot. This is a visual of the absolute or percentage number of instances in each cluster.

from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from collections import namedtuple

def k_neighbors_dist_plot(X, n_neighbors, return_distances=False, **kneighbors_kwargs):
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(**kneighbors_kwargs)
    knn.fit(X, [0]*len(X))
    distances_to_kth_neighbor = knn.kneighbors(X, n_neighbors=n_neighbors)[0][:,-1]
    distances_to_kth_neighbor = -np.sort(-distances_to_kth_neighbor)
    plt.plot(distances_to_kth_neighbor)
    plt.ylabel(f"Distance to {n_neighbors}th nearest neighbor")
    plt.xlabel("sorted instances")
    plt.gca().yaxis.grid()
    plt.show()
    
    if return_distances:
        return distances_to_kth_neighbor


def _split_n_clusters_list(n_clusters_list):
    splitting_indices = [0]
    for i in range(1, len(n_clusters_list)):
        if n_clusters_list[i - 1].n_clusters != n_clusters_list[i].n_clusters:
            splitting_indices.append(i)
            
    splits = []
    for i in range(1, len(splitting_indices)):
        splits.append(n_clusters_list[splitting_indices[i - 1]:splitting_indices[i]])
    splits.append(n_clusters_list[splitting_indices[-1]:])
    
    result = []
    for split in splits:
        x = [eps_cluster_num.eps for eps_cluster_num in split]
        y = [split[0].n_clusters] * len(split)
        result.append([x, y])
    return result

def cluster_birth_death_plot(X, eps_start=0.25, eps_stop=10.0, eps_step=0.25, return_n_clusters=False, **dbscan_kwargs):
    n_clusters_list = []
    EpsClusterNum = namedtuple('EpsClusterNum', ['eps', 'n_clusters'])
    for eps in np.arange(eps_start, eps_stop, eps_step):
        dbscan = DBSCAN(eps=eps, **dbscan_kwargs)
        dbscan.fit(X)
        n_clusters = len(np.unique(dbscan.labels_)) - (1 if -1 in dbscan.labels_ else 0)
        n_clusters_list.append(EpsClusterNum(eps=eps, n_clusters=n_clusters))
            
    plots = _split_n_clusters_list(n_clusters_list)
    for plot in plots:
        plt.plot(plot[0], plot[1])
    plt.ylabel("N Clusters")
    plt.xlabel("`eps`")
    yint = []
    locs, labels = plt.yticks()
    for each in locs:
        yint.append(int(each))
    yint = np.array(yint)
    yint = yint[yint  >= 0]
    plt.yticks(yint)
    plt.show()
    
    if return_n_clusters:
        return n_clusters_list
    
    
    
def cluster_support_plot(X=None, dbscan=None, absolute=True, **dbscan_kwargs):
    if dbscan is not None:
        supports = []
        for i in range(0, np.amax(dbscan.labels_) + 1):
            supports.append(np.sum(dbscan.labels_ == i))
    elif dbscan is None:
        if X is not None:
            dbscan = DBSCAN(**dbscan_kwargs)
            dbscan.fit(X)
            supports = []
            for i in range(0, np.amax(dbscan.labels_) + 1):
                supports.append(np.sum(dbscan.labels_ == i))
        elif X is None:
            raise Exception("if dbscan is None, X must be a dataset on which to fit DBSCAN")

    if absolute:
        x = list(range(0,np.amax(dbscan.labels_) + 1))
        plt.bar(x, supports)
        plt.xlabel("Cluster Index")
        plt.xticks(x)
        plt.ylabel("Num samples")
        plt.show()



    















Though the mnist dataset has somewhat low noise (as seen in the k-neighbors-dist plot), the cluster-birth-death plot and cluster-support plots show that DBSCAN is not very successful on this dataset. This can be indicative of several clusters of variable density, or clusters not separated regularly by enough relatively low-density space, or just an absence of useful well-delineated clusters (e.g. all instances appearing in one or several large clusters more or less together, regardless of their (in practice latent) labels, and a few instances in relatively small clusters, which aren't outliers but just small groups of "weird" legitimate instances.

X_moon_train, X_moon_test, y_moon_train, y_moon_test = train_test_split(X_moon, y_moon)
dbscan = DBSCAN(eps=0.2, min_samples=2*X_moon_train.shape[1])
clf_core = SGDClassifier()
clf = SGDClassifier()

dbscan.fit(X_moon_train)


# Keep in mind for testing purposes on a general dataset with labels on which we want to check the performance
# of a DBSCAN algorithm, the cluster indices will probably not match the labels, so something like
# `y_pred == y` will be meaningless.  
clf_core.fit(dbscan.components_, dbscan.labels_[dbscan.core_sample_indices_])
y_pred_core = clf_core.predict(X_moon_test)
clf.fit(X_moon_train[dbscan.labels_ != -1], dbscan.labels_[dbscan.labels_ != -1])
y_pred = clf.predict(X_moon_test)

acc_core = float(np.sum(y_pred_core == y_moon_test) / y_moon_test.shape[0])
acc = float(np.sum(y_pred == y_moon_test) / y_moon_test.shape[0])
print(f"Accuracy from core samples training: {acc_core} \nAccuracy from core & noncore samples training: {acc}")

Improving memory complexity¶
First thing to try is to use the OPTICS (ordering points to identify cluster structure) algorithm, which sklearn implements with the class cluster.OPTICS. Actually, not only is this a good algorithm to try for memory optimization, but it also corrects some of the problems with DBSCAN, namely the difficulty in choosing appripriate eps and min_samples and the issue of clusters of variable density.


The algorithm is rather involved, but basically the idea is to use a dendrogram to intelligently order the instances by their cluster and then by reachability. This creates a plot of hills and valleys, the valleys representing the learned clusters, the depth of a valley representing the density of the cluster (deeper valley == denser cluster). Two modes can be used: automatic- (i.e. calling fit_predict) or interactive-cluster discovery (i.e. the programmer examines a plot from which a good choice of eps for DBSCAN is chosen). Generally the default parameters will work a lot better than those of DBSCAN, but they might also likely need tuning.


Demonstration of how to choose an eps interactively, in an ideal dataset of variable cluster density (dataset is defined in code block below)



To get similar results to DBSCAN when using OPTICS automatically, set cluster_method='dbscan'. Keep in mind that DBSCAN is optimized for compute complexity, while OPTICS is optimized for memory complexity.


Another way to optimize for memory when using DBSCAN follows. Define a neighbors.NearestNeighbors object and call the radius_neighbors_graph on the dataset X to obtain a sparse matrix representation of dataset in terms of neighbors. This can be done in a memory-efficient way. Read more about this from sklearn userguide. Then fit DBSCAN on the representation, passing the argument metric='precomputed'.


Here is an example of using OPTICS interactively to select eps.

from sklearn.cluster import OPTICS, cluster_optics_dbscan
import matplotlib.gridspec as gridspec
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

############## Generate sample data
n_points_per_cluster = 250
# Make clusters with variable density
C1 = [-5, -2] + .8 * np.random.randn(n_points_per_cluster, 2)
C2 = [4, -1] + .1 * np.random.randn(n_points_per_cluster, 2)
C3 = [1, -2] + .2 * np.random.randn(n_points_per_cluster, 2)
C4 = [-2, 3] + .3 * np.random.randn(n_points_per_cluster, 2)
C5 = [3, -2] + 1.6 * np.random.randn(n_points_per_cluster, 2)
C6 = [5, 6] + 2 * np.random.randn(n_points_per_cluster, 2)
X = np.vstack((C1, C2, C3, C4, C5, C6))


def reachability_plot(X, show_outliers=True, **optics_kwargs):
    clust = OPTICS(**optics_kwargs)
    clust.fit(X)
    space = np.arange(len(X))
    reachability = clust.reachability_[clust.ordering_]
    labels = clust.labels_[clust.ordering_]
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
    G = gridspec.GridSpec(2, 3)
    ax1 = plt.subplot(G[0, :])
    num_clusters = np.amax(labels) + 1
    for cluster_index in range(0, num_clusters):
        Xk = space[labels == cluster_index]
        Rk = reachability[labels == cluster_index]
        ax1.plot(Xk, Rk, alpha=0.9)
    if show_outliers:
        ax1.plot(space[labels == -1], reachability[labels == -1], 'k.', alpha=0.3)
    ax1.set_ylabel('Reachability (epsilon distance)')
    ax1.set_title('Reachability Plot')
    
    plt.show()

optics_kwargs = {'min_samples':50, 'xi':0.05, 'min_cluster_size':0.05}
reachability_plot(X, **optics_kwargs)

Agglomerative Clustering¶
This is a hierarchical clustering algorithm - nested clusters are built by successive merging and splitting of preexisting clusters. This can be represented as a tree, where the root represents the cluster of all samples, and the leaves represent the state where each sample is its own cluster. We're going for a middle layer of the tree which minimizes some loss or maximizes some objective. The AgglomerativeClustering class implements this with various linkage criteria which are passed as hyperparameters. Here are discussed only two criteria but there are others as well:


    

  1. linkage='ward' - (default) minimizes the intracluster sum of squared differences between all clusters
    2. 

  2. linkage='single' - minimizes the distance between the nearest members of pairs of clusters
    3. 



Ward tends to lead to more even cluster sizes while single favors a "rich get richer" result. Single is more sensitive to noise but is more suitable for large datasets and non-globular shaped clusters.




A very unique and useful element of this algorithm is that it allows for the use of connectivity contraints by passing a connectivity matrix to the connectivity parameter. This could be a scipy sparse matrix with elements relating connectivity via sample indicies. This matrix can be learned by another ML algorithm, for instance neighbors.kneighbors_graph, or determined explicitly. For instance in a clustering of customers, one may only want to link customers when they're within a certain geographical distance, or shape some other similarity, even if the euclidean distance between feature vectors is small. It is usually best to use 'ward' linkage when passing connectivity contraints.


You can use the affinity='euclidean' $\in$ ('euclidean', 'manhattan', 'cosine', 'precomputed') parameter to try different metrics. If 'precomputed' is chosen then the model must be fit on a distance matrix.


There are basically two modes of using this model: a-priori number of clusters or learned number of clusters. To use the former, pass an int to n_clusters=2. To use the later, pass a float to distance_threshold, pass n_clusters=None and compute_full_tree=True. This is the linkage distance threshold above which, clusters will not be merged.


There is a nonlinear dimensionality reduction technique based on hierarchical clustering. Sklearn implements a FeatureAgglomeration class with the same API as AgglomerativeClustering, which merges similar features instead of similar instances. As with other dimensionality reduction techniques, this class implements fit, transform, and fit_transform.
